## A Prophecy Inscribed in the Stone of Time

The **Dragonborn Prophecy** is one of the oldest and most significant prophecies in **Tamriel**'s history. Transmitted across millennia by the **Elder Scrolls**, carved into the stone of **Alduin's Wall**, and preserved by the traditions of the Akaviri **Blades**, it foretells the return of the World-Eater and the emergence of the hero destined to face him.

This prophecy is remarkable for its precision — a rarity in the usually obscure and ambiguous realm of Tamrielic divination. The events it describes were fulfilled almost literally in 4E 201, when **Alduin** returned and the **Dovahkiin** (Dragonborn) emerged to fight him.

The prophecy is not the work of a single prophet or a single moment but a convergence of multiple prophetic sources across the ages, all pointing toward the same events.

## The Prophetic Text

The heart of the prophecy, as transcribed in the **Book of the Dragonborn** and preserved by the Blades, can be summarized thus:

*When misrule takes its mantle, with both moons afoul, when the cursed stars fall onto Tamriel's soil, the Wheel of Time turns to the Last Dragonborn.*

The signs point to **Skyrim**'s civil war — brothers of Nordic blood fighting among themselves. The "cursed stars" refer to cosmological events marking the beginning of the end. The "dead who walk" herald the return of the **Dragons**, creatures of a bygone age.

The prophecy indicates that these signs will converge to signal the arrival of the **Dovahkiin**, the mortal blessed by **Akatosh** with the soul and blood of a dragon — the only one capable of definitively defeating Alduin.

## The Elder Scrolls: The Primary Source

The **Elder Scrolls** are the most powerful and most mysterious prophetic artifacts in Tamriel. Neither created by the Aedra nor by the Daedra, they seem to exist outside normal causality — fragments of the very fabric of fate, readable only at the price of reason or sight.

The Dragonborn Prophecy is inscribed — or more precisely "contained" — within at least one Elder Scroll. But reading such a scroll is no simple act: the Scrolls are of infinite complexity, and their contents change depending on the reader, the moment, and the conditions of the reading.

The **Moth Priests** of the **Imperial Library** are the traditional guardians of the Scrolls within the Empire. Their prolonged reading has rendered them blind — the physical price of communion with these artifacts. Despite their blindness, they are the foremost interpreters of the prophetic fragments they have been able to decipher.

**Septimus Signus**, an eccentric scholar of the Fourth Era, devoted his life to studying one Scroll, sinking into a productive madness that allowed him to grasp certain aspects of the prophecy before losing his mind entirely.

## Alduin's Wall at Sky Haven Temple

**Alduin's Wall** is a monumental bas-relief located within the temple of **Sky Haven Temple**, a secret sanctuary of the **Blades** in the mountains of **The Reach**, in southwestern Skyrim.

Sculpted by the **Akaviri Blades** of the First Era — the warriors from **Akavir** who came to Tamriel to fight dragons and became the protectors of the Emperor's bloodline — the Wall depicts the history of Alduin and the prophecy of his return in pictorial form.

The Wall shows three main panels:

The **past**: Alduin's first defeat in the Merethic Era, when the Nordic heroes **Hakon**, **Gormlaith**, and **Felldir** used an **Elder Scroll** and the Shout **Dragonrend** to cast him into the future rather than kill him.

The **present**: the warning signs of his return — wars, prophecies, the convergence of fates.

The **future**: Alduin's re-emergence and the appearance of the Dovahkiin, the only being capable of definitively defeating him through the unique ability to absorb dragon souls.

## The Nature of the Dovahkiin

The **Dragonborn** (Dovahkiin) is not simply a talented mortal — he is a fundamentally different being, blessed (or cursed) by the god **Akatosh** himself with the soul of a **Dragon** in a mortal body.

This duality grants him several unique abilities:

The instinctive mastery of the **Thu'um** — the Voice, the power of draconic Shouts. Where an ordinary mortal must meditate for decades to master a single Shout, the Dovahkiin learns instantly by absorbing the knowledge from word walls or defeated dragons.

The ability to **absorb dragon souls**, preventing them from reincarnating. Dragons are normally immortal — when their body is destroyed, their soul persists and can be recalled by a more powerful dragon. Only the Dovahkiin can truly kill them.

An innate connection with **Akatosh**, the divine Dragon of Time, which manifests as resistance to temporal manipulation and an affinity with time magic.

## The Greybeards and High Hrothgar

The prophecy involves the **Greybeards** of **High Hrothgar** as guides and confirmers of the Dovahkiin's identity. These contemplative monks, devoted to the study of the Thu'um in the isolation of the highest mountain in Tamriel — the **Throat of the World** — are the traditional guardians of the Way of the Voice.

When the Dovahkiin manifests, the Greybeards call him through a Shout that resonates across all of Skyrim — the **Dovah Fen Mah** — to summon him to High Hrothgar and confirm his nature. This is a ritual act anticipated for generations.

**Paarthurnax**, the ancient dragon who secretly teaches the Greybeards at the summit of the Throat of the World, plays a crucial role in the prophecy. A former lieutenant of Alduin who turned against him at the bidding of **Kyne**, Paarthurnax had been awaiting his brother's return and the Dovahkiin's emergence for millennia.

## The Fulfillment in 4E 201

In 4E 201, all elements of the prophecy converged:

**Alduin** re-emerged from the temporal stream at Helgen, exactly where and when the Dovahkiin was present — a coincidence many interpret as proof of divine destiny at work.

The Dovahkiin discovered his nature at the death of his first dragon at the **Western Watchtower** near Whiterun, absorbing the creature's soul and revealing his unique ability.

The Greybeards called him. **Paarthurnax** taught him the Dragonrend Shout. The **Blades** guided him to Alduin's Wall. An **Elder Scroll** allowed him to travel back in time to learn Dragonrend from the original heroes.

The final confrontation took place in **Sovngarde** itself — the Nordic warriors' afterlife — where Alduin had taken refuge to devour the souls of heroes and grow stronger. The Dovahkiin pursued him there and defeated him with the aid of the ancient heroes.

## Unresolved Questions

The fulfilled prophecy leaves several questions open:

**Is Alduin truly dead?** His soul was not absorbed by the Dovahkiin during the final battle in Sovngarde — it dispersed. Some interpret this as meaning Alduin will one day return to fulfill his cosmic function as World-Eater at the end of the kalpa (the world's cycle).

**Is the Dovahkiin the last?** The title "Last Dragonborn" is ambiguous — last of the lineage, or last before the end of the world?

**What is the connection to Akaviri prophecies?** The Blades came from Akavir to fight dragons. Did they possess prophetic knowledge we have yet to decipher?

## The Prophetic Legacy

The Dragonborn Prophecy confirms a fundamental principle of Tamrielic metaphysics: fate exists, but it is not rigid. The Elder Scrolls show possibilities, not certainties. The Dovahkiin could have failed — the prophecy foretold his existence, not his victory.

It also reminds us that **Tamriel** is a world where heroes emerge in moments of greatest need — not by chance, but through a convergence of cosmic forces, divine wills, and individual choices that form the fabric of fate.

The Dragonborn of 4E 201 thus joins the lineage of Tamriel's prophetic heroes: the **Nerevarine**, the **Champion of Cyrodiil**, the **Eternal Champion** — ordinary individuals elevated by destiny to become instruments of cosmic change.
